name: Flee Model for South Sudan, 2013 to 2015
description: Flee is an agent-based modeling toolkit which is purpose-built for simulating the movement of individuals across geographical locations, released under a BSD 3-clause license.  Flee is currently used for modeling the movements of refugees and internally displaced persons (IDPs).  This instance of Flee is for South Sudan covering the period December 15, 2013 to August 10, 2015 (a simulation period of 604 days). During this period, 2.4 million refugees fled the country to multiple camps in neighboring countries (Kenya, Sudan, Uganda and Ethiopia).

parameters.name: maxmovespeed
parameters.description: A user can adjust the maximum movement speed of refugee agents within the model. Refugees will never move faster than this limit, but will move slower, for example, when agents stop at intermediate (non conflict-zone) locations.

parameters.name: awarenesslevel
parameters.description:
Within our simulation model, we are able to adjust our algorithm to incorporate a more wide or narrow awareness level for the agents. Agents can be aware of the presence of paths only ('Unweighted'), of only the length of the path to the nearest settlement ('Path distance only'), the type of nearest settlement ('1 link away'), the type of settlements adjacent to neighboring settlements ('2 links away'), and the type of settlements neighboring those neighbors of neighbors ('3 links away'). 
AwarenessLevel: 
-1, no weighting at all, 
0 = road only, 
1 = location, 
2 = neighbors, 
3 = region.

parameters.name: defaultmovechance
parameters.description: Move probability for agents who reside in locations other than camps and conflict zones.  That is, it is the probability of moving away from the current location.

outputs.name: sim
outputs.description: simulated population in the refugee camp

outputs.name: data
outputs.description: observed population in the refugee camp
